{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585087"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:02:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:02:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14860"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14860"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.25,0.46,0.04,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65944"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14860"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18572"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65944"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBacteria can be classified based on their cellular structure and components. Some unusual bacteria lack typical bacterial features.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a bacterium that lacks a cell wall?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chlamydia trachomatis","Rickettsia rickettsii","Mycoplasma pneumoniae","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Legionella pneumophila"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E is unique among bacteria as it completely lacks a cell wall and is bounded only by a cell membrane. This makes it naturally resistant to antibiotics that target cell wall synthesis (like penicillins). It is the smallest free-living organism capable of independent replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other organisms all possess cell walls:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ERickettsia rickettsii\u003C/strong\u003E are intracellular bacteria that possess cell walls containing peptidoglycan, though their walls are relatively weak\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-positive bacterium with a thick peptidoglycan cell wall\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELegionella pneumophila\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-negative bacterium with a typical bacterial cell wall containing peptidoglycan and an outer membrane\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mycoplasma is unique among bacteria as it lacks a cell wall and is bounded only by a cell membrane.","The absence of a cell wall makes Mycoplasma naturally resistant to beta-lactam antibiotics.","Mycoplasma is the smallest free-living organism capable of independent replication."],"references":["Onwuamaegbu ME, Belcher RA, Soare C. Cell wall-deficient bacteria as a cause of infections: a review of the clinical significance. J Int Med Res. 2005 Jan-Feb;33(1):1-20. doi: 10.1177/147323000503300101. PMID: 15651712.","Atlas, R. M., \u0026 Snyder, J. W. (2013). Handbook of media for clinical and public health microbiology. CRC Press.","Saraya T. Mycoplasma pneumoniae infection: Basics. J Gen Fam Med. 2017 Apr 17;18(3):118-125. doi: 10.1002/jgf2.15. PMID: 29264006; PMCID: PMC5689399."]},"